title: Winter Montgomery Bell MTB Time Trial Series
description:
Nashville Local Cycling Presents:  

1st Annual Winter Montgomery Bell MTB Time Trial Series!

This will be the first of three MTB time trials held this winter at Montgomery Bell MTB park.  These races will be held the first Sunday of January, February, and March and all will be against the clock.  Each race you will set your fastest time on the course with your fastest time counting and awards being given at the final race in March.  

Categories are:
Open Men
Open Women
Masters Men 40+
Singlespeed 
Junior Male
Junior Female

The first two races in January and February will not be TBRA points races however the final race in March will be a TBRA points race collecting TBRA MTB TT points and the first MTB points race of the year.  So make sure you are at the last race for sure to gain those valuable early season bonus points!  All TBRA categories will be separated out on the website for points but only the categories listed above will be awarded at the race.

This will be similar to the Snake Creek Gap TT's that a lot of guys like to do including myself.  This will be on a smaller more local scale.  We will be doing the longest lap possible at Montgomery Bell without crossing over.  Go in the trailhead and go left, take rabbit run (white), Storm Track (White), White Pine (white), continue on the race loop adding in Goat Path, heartbreak hill, cat track (blue), and finally Lonesome blue (blue) on the way out.  This will be a tough 13 mile loop and everyone will do one lap as fast as they can.  Each person will start one at a time starting at noon starting with the fastest riders to the slowest to help with congestion and trail passing.   We expect laps around 1 1/2 - 2 hours.

This will be a fun event to get everyone out racing in the winter time and get you primed up and ready for the upcoming 2016 season.

registration: Pre-Registration on USAC Website and onsite registration opens at 10:am each event day.  $20 pre-reg per day and $25 on-site.  Or $50 pre-reg for the whole series if bought online and $55 whole for the whole series on-site at the first race only.
directions: 830 Bill Duke Road, White Bluff, TN 37187.  Main Montgomery Bell MTBTrailhead.

Ride To The Sky
description: The Cookeville and Putnam County, TN area is at the heart of Tennessee’s Upper Cumberland and some of the finest cycling roads you will ever roll/climb over.  In its 3rd year, the Ride to the Sky – benefitting Cookeville Regional Foundation and Carmen’s Fund – will undergo some significant and positive changes for 2016.  First, the cycling tours will start/end at the Dogwood Park, in Cookeville.  Next, the routes will all be entirely new.  Finally, there will be 4 challenging routes (40-miler being new) from which to choose.  Some things will remain the same such as the post ride celebration with live music, locally crafted brews and nourishing BBQ with fixins.   Register for your fall challenge in the beautiful Upper Cumberland at www.usacycling.com.  We encourage early registration.
course:
You can’t find a flat ride in the Upper Cumberland.  Us locals like it that way.  For ‘16 you will have 4 route options.  All will yield the best that the fall weather has to offer.  All will have some climbing and descents.  The degree of your challenge is up to you.  Please review the route maps and descriptions at the “Routes” section of the website.
All of the 4 routes will be common to the 9.3 mile point and include the first 376’ ascent.  From this point the 20-mile route will roll on the plateau above Cookeville and ease back down the 376’ to the finish.  The other 3 routes will see all of their initial climb erased with an attention-deserving descent down Green Mtn. road – PLEASE be cautious.  It is steep.  The 40-mile route will depart from the 60 & 80 routes at the 13.3 mile point.  You’ll want to make your commitment to challenge at this point.  The 40-mile route will tax your reserves.  The 60 & 80-mile will ascend higher into the sky.
The 60 & 80-mile routes deviate at the 30.5 mile point – a decision milestone.  You should know what you have left in the tank at this point as the many rollers will have challenged you already.  Know that there is more to come on the 60-mile loop and know that the Cub Mtn. segment looms large on the 80-mile route.  Should you continue with your 80-mile challenge, remember that there will be a 5-mile segment of well packed gravel road.  Assess your equipment and/or ride gently till back on the tarmac.  Once you have put your stamp on Cub Mtn., you’ll still have smooth switchbacks on the downhill and another couple climbs before you can party at the park.  We’ll save some food and beverage for you.  All routes will be well supported with friendly and well stocked rest stops.
registration: *This years event will be limited to 350 riders.  October 1st will be the last day to register and be garanteed a T-shirt in your size.  Online registration will close at 350 riders or October 22 whichever occurs first.  Check-in and packet pickup will open at 7:00am central time the morning of the ride.
notes: The 80 & 60 mile riders will leave out at 8:00am and the 40 & 20 mile riders will leave out at 9:00am.
directions:
From Nashville I-40: take exit 286 and turn left (north) on Willow Ave. (Hwy 135).  Turn Right (East) on Spring St.. Turn Left (north) on Walnut Ave. Follow signs to parking.
From Knoxville I-40: take exit 286 and turn right (north) on Willow Ave. (Hwy 135).  Turn Right (East) on Spring St.. Turn Left (north) on Walnut Ave. Follow signs to parking.
If you are traveling in from Hwy 111 exit at the Cookeville Exit at Hwy 70 (Spring St.), turn right onto Broad St., follow signs to parking.
